Mahalanobis distance is an example of a distribution-based algorithm. It is an effective multivariate distance metric that measures the distance between a point and a distribution [96, 132, 131, 66]. It takes into consideration the correlation between features which is more suitable when features are not independent. It is best for finding multivariate outliers and finds its applications in multivariate anomaly detection, classification, and one-class classification. The Mahalanobis equation is: D = (X − μt) · C−1 · (X − μt); where X is the feature vector of a test sample, μt is the mean feature calculated from the profile template, and C−1 is the inverse covariance matrix of the user profile template.
